   {:e #blake3 "c3d319127c276937d6dbb2b4210d3f50abd422289ced4138754648d17a482ea1" :a :db/ident :v :harvest/session-braid-user-1774045342 :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "c3d319127c276937d6dbb2b4210d3f50abd422289ced4138754648d17a482ea1" :a :harvest/accomplishments :v "Session entity: :recon/trace-f8145a2f8681938e; Session entity: :recon/trace-c0d709a3c36a20ea; FUNDAMENTAL INSIGHT: The duplicate detection problem is NOT a tooling problem — it is an ATTENTION ALLOCATION problem. The system has braid task search, spec_graph_neighbors, knowledge_relevance_scan. All work. I used none of them before creating OAO, TSV-3, or the initial CTP tasks. Three duplications in one session despite having the tools to prevent all three. The pattern: when I am in GENERATIVE MODE (producing new ideas), I do not switch to VERIFICATION MODE (checking what exists). These are different cognitive states. Generative mode is divergent — explore the space, follow the reasoning, produce the insight. Verification mode is convergent — query the store, compare with existing, identify overlaps. Asking an agent in generative mode to voluntarily switch to verification mode is a PROCESS OBLIGATION that decays under pressure (SEED.md S2). This is identical to the Basin A/Basin B problem: methodology (verification) competes with creation (generation) for the same attention budget. The solution MUST be structural, not procedural. The agent cannot be TOLD to search first — it must be FORCED to search first by the system architecture.; Session entity: :recon/trace-77d4bb4b64c6e10a; SEARCH-BEFORE-CONFIRM: The preview on braid task create is a refinement of CRB gate (INV-GUIDANCE-025). The existing CRB gate BLOCKS when 3+ matches found. The preview SHOWS matches for ANY count >= 1. It is a mirror, not a wall. Implementation: in commands/task.rs create(), after parsing title but before create_task_datoms(), call knowledge_relevance_scan(short_title(&title), &store). If results non-empty AND --force not passed, display results and exit 0 (not error — it's informational). Agent sees related work at the exact moment of creation, before sunk cost accumulates. ~20 lines. Composes with TAP-SPLIT: when title is short, the keyword search is more precise. Composes with AR concentration: if agent has been in INTERFACE namespace all session, preview shows ALL recent INTERFACE work. Does NOT require a new EPIC — it is a subtask of existing Value Slice 1 CRB work (t-651624c3).; Session entity: :recon/trace-e34a17dddc8300dc; Session entity: :recon/trace-4c404502ba221596; Session entity: :recon/trace-44ebbd7c090e6094; STRUCTURAL ANALYSIS: What does 'forced to search first' mean? The CRB gate (INV-GUIDANCE-025) already exists as a concept — when reconciliation finds 3+ matches, the command requires --reconciled flag. But the CRB gate runs on the OUTPUT text of the command (the observation body, the task title). It does NOT run on the INTENT that precedes the command. The agent's reasoning goes: (1) I have an idea → (2) I formulate it as a task → (3) braid task create runs CRB on the FORMULATED text → (4) CRB finds or doesn't find matches. The problem: step 3 runs CRB on the FULL TITLE (500 chars of BACKGROUND) which dilutes the signal. TAP-SPLIT fixes this by making the title short. But there's a deeper issue: CRB runs AFTER the agent has already committed cognitive effort to formulating the task. Sunk cost bias makes the agent want to proceed even when matches are found. The maximally structural solution: CRB should run at INTENT time, not at COMMAND time. When the agent THINKS about creating a task (before typing the command), the system should already be showing related work. This is exactly what the Ambient Reconciliation concentration detector does — it surfaces related work through braid status BEFORE the agent creates anything. The two systems compose: AR concentration prevents the agent from entering a neighborhood without seeing what's there. CRB gate prevents the agent from creating in a neighborhood without reconciling. Together they form a two-layer defense: awareness (AR) + enforcement (CRB).; Session entity: :recon/trace-ebd32622ef41e3e8; Session entity: :recon/trace-a69415faefa2cc4b; FIRST-PRINCIPLES ROOT CAUSE: Is the generative→verification mode switch inherently hard for LLMs, or is it a solvable architecture problem? ANALYSIS: LLMs are autoregressive — they generate token by token, each conditioned on prior tokens. Once the generative trajectory is underway (I have an idea for an EPIC about output-as-observation...), the attention weights are configured for ELABORATION, not VERIFICATION. Switching to verification requires a DISCONTINUITY in the generation — the model must stop mid-thought, invoke an external tool, process the results, and POTENTIALLY ABANDON its current trajectory based on what it finds. This is cognitively expensive (in k* terms) and psychologically aversive (sunk cost). THREE POSSIBLE SOLUTIONS ranked by structural strength: (1) WEAKEST — Process reminder: Tell the agent to search first. This is what CLAUDE.md methodology sections do. Decays within 15-20 turns (Basin B drift). We've proven this fails. (2) MEDIUM — CRB gate on task create with TAP-SPLIT: The gate runs on short titles, catches more duplicates via keyword density. But the agent has already formulated the task — sunk cost bias. (3) STRONGEST — Make braid task create ITSELF run search and SHOW results inline before confirming. Not a gate (which blocks), but a PREVIEW (which informs). When I type 'braid task create Auto-observation for...', BEFORE creating, the command runs braid task search on the title keywords and shows: 'Related: t-e2e64fe4 EPIC: Zero-Cost Methodology (Auto-observation + smart harvest)... Proceed? [y/--force]'. This is the structural solution: the search is EMBEDDED in the creation command. The agent cannot create without seeing what exists. No separate tool invocation needed. No mode switch. The search happens at the EXACT moment the agent is about to commit.; Session entity: :recon/trace-6057d2cfe76af1a1; Session entity: :recon/trace-cc0208221e2870ee; Session entity: :recon/trace-6e047e4945daae78; META-OBSERVATION: After 3 audit rounds, I notice I keep finding the SAME failure mode — creating work that duplicates existing work. OAO duplicated ZCM. The initial TSV tasks ignored ACP. The CTP tasks initially ignored the existing ContextSection architecture. Each time, the fix was: look at what exists, then integrate. The pattern suggests a STRUCTURAL problem with how I work, not just a task definition problem. The structural problem: I generate proposals from FIRST PRINCIPLES reasoning without adequate grounding in WHAT EXISTS. The observe→crystallize→task pipeline starts with observe (what I think) rather than starting with QUERY (what the store knows). The maximally accretive improvement to my workflow is: BEFORE crystallizing any new EPIC, run braid task search on the 3 most important keywords from the proposal. If matches exist, the new work is an EXTENSION of existing work, not a new EPIC. This is not a braid feature request — it's a METHODOLOGY improvement. The system already has the tools (task search, spec_graph_neighbors). The gap is in my PROCESS of using them.; Session entity: :recon/trace-2d75e566a52fe8df; Session entity: :recon/trace-2af568a9de5a0756\nSession entity: :task/t-483426c9" :op :assert}
